'''Tatsuta Goboyama No. 3 Kofun''' (竜田御坊山3号墳, also called Tatsuta Goboyama Kofun) was a [[Kofun]] located in [[:en:Ikaruga, Nara|Ikaruga, Nara]], [[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]]. Part of the Tatsuta Goboyama Kofun Cluster, it was a {{ill|Round Kofun|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}. The mound has since disappeared, but the excavated burial goods are Historic Site1 as National [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]].

== Overview ==

Tatsuta Goboyama No. 3 Kofun was a small round tumulus built on the southern slope of a hill in the northwestern Nara Basin, north of {{ill|Tatsuta Shrine (Nara)|ja|龍田神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tatsuta Shrine (Nara)|qq=}} and southwest of [[:en:Hōryū-ji|Hōryū-ji]]. It was part of the Tatsuta Goboyama Kofun Cluster, with two other tumuli (Nos. 1 and 2) located to the southwest. The tumulus was discovered during a residential development project in 1965 (Showa 40), after which it was excavated and subsequently destroyed{{Sfn|Goboyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1981}}.

The tumulus is estimated to have been circular, with a diameter of about 8 meters and a height of 2.5 meters{{Sfn|Goboyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1981}}. The burial facility was a {{ill|Cave Tomb-style stone coffin|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb-style stone coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}}, opening southward and containing a lacquered house-shaped {{ill|tōkan|ja|陶棺|1=Ceramic Coffins|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tōkan|13=User:Immanuelle/Ceramic Coffins|qq=}}. The adoption of the Cave Tomb-style stone coffin and lacquered coffin indicates the high social status of the interred individual. However, the hastily prepared lacquered tōkan, with mismatched components and repair marks, suggests an emergency burial{{Sfn|Kinuhata et al.|2021}}.

burial goods recovered from the coffin include human remains (a 14–15-year-old male), an amber pillow, a tri-colored lidded inkstone, and a glass writing tube, all of which are rare and noteworthy. The kofun is dated to the mid-7th century, during the terminal phase of the [[:en:Kofun period|Kofun period]]{{Sfn|Kinuhata et al.|2021}}.

The excavated burial goods were Historic Site1 as National [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]] in 1981 (Showa 56)<ref name="National Heritage Database"/>.

== burial ==

The burial facility consisted of a {{ill|Cave Tomb-style stone coffin|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb-style stone coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}}, constructed with granite. It comprised three main components: a base stone, a lid stone, and a sealing stone. The area of these components are as follows{{Sfn|Kinuhata et al.|2021}}:
* Lid stone: Maximum length 2.86 m, width 1.61 m, height 0.93 m
* Base stone: Maximum length 2.93 m, width 1.67 m, height 0.57 m
* Sealing stone: Maximum width 1.11 m, height 0.90 m, thickness 0.35 m

The interior of the coffin was coated with plaster, enhancing its sealing capability. The lacquered tōkan inside the coffin, although of high status, showed signs of emergency preparation, with mismatched components and hasty repairs{{Sfn|Kinuhata et al.|2021}}.

== Cultural burial goods ==

burial goods excavated from the tōkan include:
* Amber pillow: Analyzed as originating from Kuji, Iwate Prefecture
* Tri-colored lidded inkstone: Possibly imported from China or the Korean Peninsula
* Glass writing tube: May correspond to writing tools described in Wang Xizhi’s "Pen Treatise"

== Historical Context ==

The interred individual is hypothesized to be a member of the Upper Miyake Royal Family, descendants of Prince Shōtoku. The cluster’s proximity to key temples like [[:en:Hōryū-ji|Hōryū-ji]] suggests a connection to the region’s political and religious developments{{Sfn|Kinuhata et al.|2021}}.

